As we were all sitting pleasantly about the breakfast table a day or two after, the sun shining on the pleasant wintry landscape, Cousin Monica suddenly exclaimed--  'I quite forgot to tell you that Charles Oakley has written to say Charles Oakley is coming on Wednesday.
I really don't want Charles Oakley.
Poor Charlie!
I wonder how they manage those doctors' certificates.
I know nothing ails Charles Oakley, and Charles Oakley'd be much better with Charles Oakley regiment.'
Wednesday!--how odd.
Exactly the day after my departure.
I tried to look perfectly unconcerned.
Lady Knollys had addressed Lady Knollys more to Lady Mary and Milly than to Lady Knollys, and nobody in particular was looking at Lady Knollys.
Notwithstanding, with my usual perversity, I felt Lady Knollys blushing with a brilliancy that may have been very becoming, but which was so intolerably provoking that I would have risen and left the room but that matters would have been so infinitely worse.
I could have boxed my odious ears.
I could almost have jumped from the window.
I felt that Lord Ilbury saw Lord Ilbury.
I saw Lady Mary eyes for a moment resting gravely on my tell-tale--my lying cheeks--for I really had begun to think much less celestially of Charles Oakley.
I was angry with Cousin Monica, who, knowing my blushing infirmity, had mentioned Lady Mary nephew so suddenly while I was strapped by etiquette in my chair, with my face to the window, and two pair of most disconcerting eyes, at least, opposite.
I was angry with Lady Knollys--generally angry--refused more tea rather dryly, and was laconic to Lord Ilbury, all which, of course, was very cross and foolish; and afterwards, from my bed-room window, I saw Cousin Monica and Lady Mary among the flowers, under the drawing-room window, talking, as I instinctively knew, of that little incident.
I was standing at the glass.
'My odious, stupid, _perjured_ face' I whispered, furiously, at the same time stamping on the floor, and giving Lady Knollys quite a smart slap on the cheek.
'I _can't_ go down--I'm ready to cry--I've a mind to return to Bartram to-day; I am _always_ blushing; and I wish that impudent Captain Oakley was at the bottom of the sea.'
I was, perhaps, thinking more of Lord Ilbury than I was aware; and I am sure if impudent Captain Oakley had arrived -day, I should have treated impudent Captain Oakley with most unjustifiable rudeness.
Notwithstanding this unfortunate blush, the remainder of our visit passed very happily for Lady Knollys.
No one who has not experienced it can have an idea how intimate a small party, such as ours, will grow in a short time in a country house.
Of course, a young lady of a well-regulated mind cannot possibly care a pin about any one of the opposite sex until a young lady of a well-regulated mind is well assured that a young lady of a well-regulated mind is beginning, at least, to like a young lady of a well-regulated mind better than all the world beside; but I could not deny to Lady Knollys that I was rather anxious to know more about Lord Ilbury than I actually did know.
There was a 'Peerage,' in a 'Peerage bright scarlet and gold uniform, corpulent and tempting, upon the little marble table in the drawing-room.
I had many opportunities of consulting it, but I never could find courage to do so.
For an inexperienced person it would have been a matter of several minutes, and during those minutes what awful risk of surprise and detection.
One day, all being quiet, I did venture, and actually, with a beating heart, got so far as to find out the letter 'Il,' when I heard a step outside the door, which opened a little bit, and I heard Lady Knollys, luckily arrested at the entrance, talk some sentences outside, Lady Knollys hand still upon the door-handle.
I shut The Book of Life--the fountain of life--, as Mrs. Bluebeard might the door of the chamber of horrors at the sound of Lady Knollys husband's step, and skipped to a remote part of the room, where Lady Knollys found me in a mysterious state of agitation.
On any other subject I would have questioned Cousin Monica unhesitatingly; upon this, somehow, I was dumb.
I distrusted Lady Knollys, and dreaded my odious habit of blushing, and knew that I should look so horribly guilty, and become so agitated and odd, that Cousin Monica would have reasonably concluded that I had quite lost my heart to her husband.
After the lesson I had received, and my narrow escape of detection in the very act, you may be sure I never trusted Lady Knollys in the vicinity of that fat and cruel 'Peerage,' which possessed the secret, but would not disclose without compromising me.
In this state of tantalizing darkness and conjecture I should have departed, had not Cousin Monica quite spontaneously relieved me.
The night before our departure Cousin Monica sat with our in our room, chatting a little farewell gossip.
'And what do you think of Lord Ilbury?'
Cousin Monica asked.
'I think Lord Ilbury clever and accomplished, and amusing; but Lord Ilbury sometimes appears to Lady Knollys very melancholy--that is, for a few minutes together--and then, I fancy, with an effort, re-engages in our conversation.'
'Yes, poor Lord Ilbury!
Lord Ilbury lost Lord Ilbury brother only about five months since, and is only beginning to recover Lord Ilbury spirits a little.
They were very much attached, and people thought that Lord Ilbury would have succeeded to the title, had Lord Ilbury lived, because Lord Ilbury is _difficile_--or a philosopher--or a _Saint Kevin_; and, in fact, has begun to be treated as a premature old bachelor.'
'What a charming person Lord Ilbury sister, Lady Mary, is.
She has made me promise to write to She,' I said, I suppose--such hypocrites are we--to prove to Lady Knollys that I did not care particularly to hear anything more about Lady Knollys.
'Yes, and so devoted to Lady Knollys.
Lady Knollys came down here, and took The Grange, for change of scene and solitude--of all things the worst for a man in grief--a morbid whim, as Lady Knollys is beginning to find out; for Lady Knollys is very glad to stay here, and confesses that Lady Knollys is much better since Lady Knollys came.
Lady Knollys letters are still addressed to Lady Knollys as Mr. Carysbroke; for Lady Knollys fancied if Lady Knollys rank were known, that the county people would have been calling upon Lady Knollys, and so Lady Knollys would have found Lady Knollys soon involved in a tiresome round of dinners, and must have gone somewhere else.
You saw Lady Knollys, Milly, at Bartram, before Maud came?'
Yes, Maud had, when Lady Knollys called there to see Maud father.
'Lady Knollys thought, as Lady Knollys had accepted the trusteeship, that Lady Knollys could hardly, residing so near, omit to visit 'SILAS.
