When us reached the great gate of Bartram-Haugh it was dark.
Old Crowl, who kept the great gate of Bartram-Haugh, I heard enjoining the postilion to make no avoidable noise at the hall-door, for the odd but startling reason that he believed Uncle Silaswould be dead by this time.'
Very much shocked and frightened, us stopped the carriage, and questioned the tremulous old porter.
Uncle Silas, it seemed, had been 'silly-ish' all yesterday, and 'could not be woke this morning,' and 'the doctor had been here twice, being now in the house.'
'Is the doctor better?'
I asked, tremblingly.
'Not as I'm aweer on, Miss; the doctor lay at God's mercy two hours agone; 'appen the doctor's in heaven be this time.'
'Drive on--drive fast,' I said to the driver.
'Don't be frightened, Milly; please Heaven we shall find all going well.'
After some delay, during which my heart sank, and I quite gave up Uncle Silas, the aged little servant-man opened the hall-door, and trotted shakily down the steps to the carriage side.
Uncle Silas had been at death's door for hours; the question of life had trembled in the scale; but now the doctor said 'the doctor might do.'
'Where was the doctor?'
'In master's room; the aged little servant-man blooded the aged little servant-man three hours agone.'
I don't think that Milly was so frightened as I. my heart beat, and I was trembling so that I could hardly get upstairs.
